My MCP client implements JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdio transport. When I send requests, I use the Content-Length header format required by MCP. I write `Content-Length: {len(payload)}

{json_payload}` to the server's stdin. For responses, I parse the exact same format - I read until I encounter `

` to get the header, extract the Content-Length value, then read exactly that many bytes for the JSON body. My _send_jsonrpc function handles this low-level protocol. If you're getting parsing errors, check that your server responds with proper Content-Length headers and that the JSON is valid. I also maintain a global message ID counter (_next_id) that increments for every request, ensuring unique IDs across all connected MCP servers.
